  "physics_explanation": "Type-II SPDC in BBO crystal generates orthogonally polarized photon pairs at 810nm from 405nm pump photons. The PBS spatially separates signal (H-polarized) and idler (V-polarized) photons into upper and lower arms. Half-wave plates rotate both polarizations to the same state, making photons indistinguishable. When path lengths are matched at the 50:50 beam splitter, quantum interference causes both photons to bunch and exit through the same port due to bosonic statistics, creating a characteristic dip in coincidence counts. The delay stage scans the relative arrival time, revealing the two-photon interference pattern with visibility determined by photon indistinguishability.",
  "expected_outcome": "As the delay stage is scanned, coincidence counts between SPAD 1 and SPAD 2 will show a characteristic dip (the Hong-Ou-Mandel dip) when the path lengths are matched. At zero delay, coincidences drop to near zero (ideally 50% reduction for perfect visibility) because indistinguishable photons bunch together and exit the same output port due to quantum interference. The dip width (typically 100-200 femtoseconds FWHM) is inversely proportional to the photon bandwidth, and visibility greater than 90% indicates high photon indistinguishability. This demonstrates the purely quantum nature of two-photon interference, as classical waves would show no such effect.",
